{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Without considering RGE, only 16 of all the 124 U(2) 5 -invariant operators affect Z-and W -pole observables.",
    "These are the bosonic operators O HW B and O HD (giving flavor-universal effects), the four-lepton operator C ijji ℓℓ (that affects the extraction of G F), and all operators in table 2 except for C [33] Hu (since there are no top quarks at the Z-pole).",
    "However, upon including RGE, 123 out of 124 operators are constrained by the EW sector (only O H is not), and 44 of these operators receive bounds stronger than 1 TeV.",
    "The common feature among these 44 operators is that almost all of them contain top quarks, which yields substantial RG contributions to EW operators when closing the top loop and attaching Higgses.",
    "Interestingly, even though top quarks are not produced directly at the Z-pole, RG effects allow for competitive indirect bounds on top-quark operators via Z-pole observables, as recently highlighted in [58]."
  ],
